04266nam a22006735i 9780804799638DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015041710  a97808047996387 a10.1515/97808047996382doi  a(DE-B1597)564082  a(OCoLC)1178769686  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aRA644.Y4bA64 2016 4aRA644.Y4bA64 2017 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a614.5412231 aApel, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFeverish Bodies, Enlightened Minds :bScience and the Yellow Fever Controversy in the Early American Republic /cThomas Apel. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Contexts and Causes -- t2. "Declare the Past" -- t3. "Nature Is the Great Experimenter" -- t4. "Let Not God Intervene" -- t5. "In Politics As Well As Medicine"; or, The Arrogance of the Enlightened -- tConclusion: "A New Era in the Science of Medicine"? -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1793 to 1805, yellow fever devastated U.S. port cities in a series of terrifying epidemics. The search for the cause and prevention of the disease involved many prominent American intellectuals, including Noah Webster and Benjamin Rush. This investigation produced one of the most substantial and innovative outpourings of scientific thought in early American history. But it also led to a heated and divisive debate-both political and theological-around the place of science in American society. Feverish Bodies, Enlightened Minds opens an important window onto the conduct of scientific inquiry in the early American republic. The debate between "contagionists," who thought the disease was imported, and "localists," who thought it came from domestic sources, reflected contemporary beliefs about God and creation, the capacities of the human mind, and even the appropriate direction of the new nation. Through this thoughtful investigation of the yellow fever epidemic and engaging examination of natural science in early America, Thomas Apel demonstrates that the scientific imaginations of early republicans were far broader than historians have realized: in order to understand their science, we must understand their ideas about God.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDiseasesxCauses and theories of causationxHistoryy18th century. 0aDiseaseszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aEpidemicszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aMedical scienceszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aYellow feverxEtiologyxHistoryy18th century. 0aYellow feverzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 4acommon sense. 4acontagionist. 4adisease causation. 4aearly republic. 4ahistory of science and medicine. 4alocalist. 4amiasmatist. 4ayellow fever. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804799638zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799638.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles